WEBVTT

1
00:01:38.150 --> 00:01:41.770
<i>Transcribed by Clarity</i>

2
00:02:48.630 --> 00:02:50.100
Do you have any food?

3
00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:54.070
I'm very hungry.

4
00:03:16.430 --> 00:03:17.830
Let down your hair.

5
00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:22.470
You do not pass for a boy.

6
00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:27.170
Let down your hair.

7
00:03:38.670 --> 00:03:40.230
I'm not afraid.

8
00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:45.170
Travelers spoke in these
hills of the hero Robin Hood.

9
00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:47.800
He protected the weak.

10
00:03:55.570 --> 00:03:57.140
Nobody protects the weak.

11
00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:00.770
And he was no hero.

12
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.900
He observed thrice a day
and gave silver the poor.

13
00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:06.200
And he had the love of Lady Marian.

14
00:04:06.280 --> 00:04:07.660
Is that not a hero?

15
00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:10.350
Lady Marian was taken
from an old Shephard’s tale

16
00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:13.480
by a story teller unfortunately
drunker than I am.

17
00:04:14.300 --> 00:04:17.200
She was the great love of Robin Hood.

18
00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:23.510
There is no great love
for one such as him.

19
00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:28.120
I know who met this man...

20
00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:30.120
Would you like a little secret?

21
00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:32.370
I would.

22
00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:35.900
He never prayed once in his life.

23
00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:42.070
These tales spread across the land.
lies upon lies.

24
00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.470
He was a murderous brigand.

25
00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:50.280
Who perhaps cut the throat of a
sheriff and a long line of others.

26
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:52.600
People saw meaning where there was none.

27
00:04:54.250 --> 00:04:55.910
He was not a hero.

28
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.520
He robbed and killed for the joy of it.
Nothing more.

29
00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:06.200
Those who you met.

30
00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:10.670
Did they say he felt
remorse for his crimes?

31
00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:16.900
I suspect he felt tired.

32
00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:23.370
I would say that if you meet this villain
Robin Hood.

33
00:05:23.450 --> 00:05:27.250
you should make haste away and
keep whatever life you have left here.

34
00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:15.190
Who is your kin?

35
00:07:17.900 --> 00:07:21.770
William Wainwright. of Pickering.

36
00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:24.230
Pickering?

37
00:07:26.070 --> 00:07:27.470
Father?

38
00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:30.570
Grandfather?

39
00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:39.830
You should have bathed.
Or waited for the wind to change.

40
00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:44.420
Or kept your weight on your back foot.

41
00:07:46.900 --> 00:07:49.870
That's all... you did wrong.

42
00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:12.570
They sing lies.

43
00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:15.830
These foolish common folk.

44
00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:20.030
Lies of his heroism and goodness.

45
00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:23.700
But blood debts are owed.

46
00:09:25.070 --> 00:09:28.200
And generations of his victims haunt him.

47
00:09:29.830 --> 00:09:31.300
For. in truth.

48
00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:35.310
none was more wicked and wanted

49
00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:38.070
than the murderous bandit Robin Hood.

50
00:09:39.770 --> 00:09:41.670
And his Little John.

51
00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:47.290
Speak to Thomas.

52
00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:51.260
He was hanged in the South.

53
00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:52.940
Will?

54
00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:55.100
They gutted him.

55
00:09:56.830 --> 00:09:58.770
I have no one else to ask.

56
00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:02.070
What happened?

57
00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:06.030
My name is Edward.

58
00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:08.200
Who was Edward?

59
00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:12.900
Met him on the road ten summers ago.

60
00:10:13.250 --> 00:10:14.740
His brother died.

61
00:10:14.820 --> 00:10:18.040
and he was going to grow ryes.
and peas on his brother's land.

62
00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:21.670
No one knew Edward's face.

63
00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:24.760
So I killed him.

64
00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:27.230
Now I am Edward.

65
00:10:28.360 --> 00:10:30.430
And Margaret is a good wife.

66
00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.300
It's a good farm.

67
00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:34.770
What happened?

68
00:10:35.960 --> 00:10:38.160
A family on the land found me out.

69
00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:41.440
He took my farm. he took my Margaret.

70
00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:43.540
He tried to take my life.

71
00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:48.820
I cannot take back alone what's mine.

72
00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:50.300
It's not yours.

73
00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:53.670
It's my family.

74
00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:00.000
I'm tired. John.

75
00:11:01.570 --> 00:11:02.970
Edward.

76
00:11:05.270 --> 00:11:06.770
I'm tired. Edward.

77
00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:14.570
It will be an mighty battle.

78
00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:16.870
One for the stories.

79
00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:26.060
-They are strong.
-Aye.

80
00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:28.430
They come from an old family.

81
00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:30.870
They say they are from Viking blood.

82
00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.760
There is a story that once
their elder father fought a bear.

83
00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:39.870
It will be a mighty battle. Robin.

84
00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:44.300
How many are there?

85
00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:47.500
Four... five.

86
00:11:47.970 --> 00:11:49.630
Together. we can best them.

87
00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:54.500
We will likely die.

88
00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:30.270
Robin.

89
00:13:31.830 --> 00:13:33.230
Robin.

90
00:13:34.600 --> 00:13:35.810
Fred.

91
00:13:38.830 --> 00:13:40.570
This is a good adventure.

92
00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:43.830
Good adventure.

93
00:13:46.800 --> 00:13:49.780
Do you remember when we met the potter

94
00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:53.180
did we leave him naked or did we kill him?

95
00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:55.020
When I tried to tell the story

96
00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:56.750
someone said we left him naked.

97
00:13:57.300 --> 00:13:58.870
I couldn't remember.

98
00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:02.360
You always told it well. Robin.

99
00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.370
Why would we leave him naked?

100
00:14:06.700 --> 00:14:08.100
I don't know.

101
00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:11.400
We were just...

102
00:14:12.500 --> 00:14:16.370
-We never met a Potter.
-What do you mean. we've never met him?

103
00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:20.580
I mean. that never happened.
It's just a story you heard somewhere.

104
00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:25.790
But even if we did meet a potter.
we killed him.

105
00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:28.510
I would have remembered
if it were a story.

106
00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:30.630
Yeah.

107
00:14:31.030 --> 00:14:32.470
Tell me about your wife.

108
00:14:35.270 --> 00:14:36.670
Margaret.

109
00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:39.830
She is a good woman.

110
00:14:40.370 --> 00:14:43.300
She's very good woman.

111
00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:45.870
She teaches me prayers for us.

112
00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:47.360
Paint a portrait.

113
00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:50.570
Paint a portrait?

114
00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:54.630
Paint a portrait.

115
00:14:58.900 --> 00:15:03.430
She has hair that's... red.

116
00:15:04.100 --> 00:15:05.480
Red... like?

117
00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:08.800
Red like fresh blood.

118
00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:09.950
No. no.

119
00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:15.200
Something that's red and that's good.
Like a...

120
00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:22.000
Like the setting sun.

121
00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:25.030
Like the setting summer sun.

122
00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:28.200
Margaret's a good wife.

123
00:15:28.870 --> 00:15:32.030
with a hair that is red
like the setting summer sun.

124
00:15:33.700 --> 00:15:35.780
she cares for me.

125
00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:38.440
and I care for her.

126
00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:47.170
Robin.

127
00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:49.870
The open runs past the mountains...

128
00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:54.690
many places to begin again.

129
00:15:59.230 --> 00:16:01.300
I do not aim to begin again.

130
00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:08.270
I aim for a right death.

131
00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:52.490
Go! Hendri!

132
00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:54.680
No. Hendri! Run!

133
00:17:54.770 --> 00:17:56.100
Run! No...

134
00:17:56.180 --> 00:17:57.980
-Hendri!
-Come on!

135
00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:00.430
Hendri. get the others!

136
00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:02.270
Edward!

137
00:18:03.470 --> 00:18:05.960
-Edward.
-My love!

138
00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.660
Watch over Little Margaret.

139
00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:11.730
You are safe.

140
00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:13.570
You are safe. daughter.

141
00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:19.600
Let us prey.

142
00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:23.070
<i>O Lord</i>

143
00:20:23.170 --> 00:20:24.570
<i>Our God.</i>

144
00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:28.830
<i>Grant us the grace to desire
thee with our whole hearts.</i>

145
00:20:29.270 --> 00:20:30.830
Come on now. pray.

146
00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:34.270
<i>And in finding thee. we may love thee </i>.</font>

147
00:20:34.430 --> 00:20:35.820
<i>And in loving thee</i>

148
00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:39.900
<i>we may hate those sins from
which thou has redeemed us.</i>

149
00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:43.200
<i>For the sake of Jesus Christ. Amen.</i>

150
00:20:45.070 --> 00:20:46.470
<i>Amen.</i>

151
00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:48.340
Good.

152
00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:00.810
I'm sorry.

153
00:22:04.030 --> 00:22:05.470
I'm sorry.

154
00:22:06.870 --> 00:22:08.750
It was that when I woke.

155
00:22:11.460 --> 00:22:13.050
It was that when I woke.

156
00:22:14.290 --> 00:22:15.690
Cousin.

157
00:22:16.370 --> 00:22:17.880
It was that when I woke.

158
00:22:19.310 --> 00:22:20.710
Sorry!

159
00:23:57.640 --> 00:23:59.600
<i>We cry to the O'Lord.</i>

160
00:24:01.250 --> 00:24:05.080
<i>Do thou have mercy upon us...</i>

161
00:24:05.210 --> 00:24:07.230
<i>and grant us forgiveness.</i>

162
00:24:07.310 --> 00:24:11.230
<i>O King of heaven and Everlasting Lord.</i>

163
00:24:11.610 --> 00:24:15.380
<i>receive our prayers which we pour forth</i>

164
00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:18.620
<i>And grant forgiveness.</i>

165
00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:23.180
<i>Sick. bring forth the captive.</i>

166
00:24:23.270 --> 00:24:27.170
<i>Help the widow and the orphan. </i>

167
00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:30.880
<i>And grant forgiveness.</i>

168
00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:35.530
<i>We have sinned and departed
from thee</i>

169
00:24:35.610 --> 00:24:41.930
<i>Will thou. Redeemer of all.
save us...</i>

170
00:24:42.010 --> 00:24:44.150
<i>and grant forgiveness.</i>

171
00:24:44.230 --> 00:24:46.920
<i>Have mercy on the penitents. </i>

172
00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:51.620
<i>And wash away the stains of sin.</i>

173
00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:55.000
<i>And grant forgiveness. </i>

174
00:24:56.700 --> 00:24:58.100
<i>Amen.</i>

175
00:25:52.460 --> 00:25:53.860
Godwyn!

176
00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:02.430
Please...

177
00:28:33.870 --> 00:28:35.300
Margaret? Margaret!

178
00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:38.080
No! No!

179
00:28:41.190 --> 00:28:43.840
John! No!

180
00:28:48.710 --> 00:28:51.370
Little John!

181
00:28:58.200 --> 00:29:00.230
Twenty winters ago...

182
00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:04.670
you murdered my cousin.
Walter of Hathersage.

183
00:29:05.720 --> 00:29:10.460
You have now murdered
my son. and my grand son.

184
00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:13.120
As weregild.

185
00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:19.860
I will accept your life. and
the life of your daughter.

186
00:31:54.330 --> 00:31:59.590
No! No!

187
00:33:09.350 --> 00:33:10.740
Robin?

188
00:33:11.670 --> 00:33:15.560
I've heard stories of
a priory hidden away.

189
00:33:16.780 --> 00:33:20.800
There's a Prioress there who's
older than anyone remembers.

190
00:33:21.710 --> 00:33:23.640
She has a healing magic.

191
00:33:24.570 --> 00:33:26.030
I'll take you to her.

192
00:33:26.430 --> 00:33:28.000
She'll get you well again.

193
00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:31.370
I've heard incredible stories.

194
00:34:32.220 --> 00:34:35.270
Robin. We must leave.

195
00:34:36.470 --> 00:34:37.970
They will be hunting us.

196
00:35:14.780 --> 00:35:16.180
Look at the snow.

197
00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:21.170
It's strange for it to fall this late.

198
00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:26.830
But it will stand the ground.

199
00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:31.630
The Lord has his back.

200
00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:26.500
A man brought you here.

201
00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:30.920
He sealed your wounds with fire.
and he didn't do a poor job.

202
00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:34.600
You've been here six days.

203
00:36:35.830 --> 00:36:37.800
You have wounds in your abdomen.

204
00:36:38.640 --> 00:36:41.270
Ribs and a leg badly broken.

205
00:36:43.230 --> 00:36:45.370
Do you understand my words?

206
00:36:49.430 --> 00:36:50.830
Yes.

207
00:36:51.450 --> 00:36:53.380
You are at the Priory of St Clement.

208
00:36:53.470 --> 00:36:55.030
For a place for you to heal.

209
00:36:56.010 --> 00:36:57.870
Well. what town?

210
00:36:58.300 --> 00:36:59.800
There is no town.

211
00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:03.570
Do you know the story of Saul?

212
00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:06.550
What?

213
00:37:07.090 --> 00:37:09.850
There goes. there once was a man. Saul.

214
00:37:10.270 --> 00:37:13.570
a breather of menaces
against disciples of the Lord.

215
00:37:14.270 --> 00:37:18.170
He came to the prince of priests.
and asked of him letters into Damascus.

216
00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:22.650
To the synagogues; that if he across
any men or women of this life.

217
00:37:22.730 --> 00:37:24.980
he should lead them bound...

218
00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:28.200
That is all we need to do.

219
00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:30.600
Just a few drops.

220
00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:34.970
It was not too painful.

221
00:37:36.830 --> 00:37:38.230
It was not.

222
00:37:42.570 --> 00:37:44.170
I'm Sister Brigid.

223
00:37:45.100 --> 00:37:46.500
What is your name?

224
00:37:48.670 --> 00:37:50.070
Randolph.

225
00:37:54.370 --> 00:37:56.600
I owe you an apology. Randolph.

226
00:37:57.430 --> 00:37:58.870
What apology?

227
00:38:01.210 --> 00:38:03.450
You begged from me to let you die.

228
00:38:04.830 --> 00:38:06.430
And I did not.

229
00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:11.260
-You said it was right.
-I was with fever.

230
00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:14.830
Well your fever is passed.

231
00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:17.800
Rest now Randolph.

232
00:38:41.200 --> 00:38:44.200
Your body is covered in scars.

233
00:39:01.270 --> 00:39:04.110
Do you mean anyone in the Priory harm?

234
00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:08.900
I do not.

235
00:39:19.060 --> 00:39:22.170
Will any harm follow you here?

236
00:39:23.800 --> 00:39:25.270
It will not.

237
00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:37.400
You will do them no harm.

238
00:40:09.500 --> 00:40:11.070
Now. back to bed.

239
00:40:26.630 --> 00:40:28.120
Now. back to the door.

240
00:40:56.200 --> 00:40:57.830
Now open the door.

241
00:41:16.670 --> 00:41:18.500
Go as far as you'd like.

242
00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:17.800
Can you row yet?

243
00:43:20.250 --> 00:43:22.380
There is a boat on the West Shore.

244
00:43:24.700 --> 00:43:26.100
It's alright.

245
00:43:27.430 --> 00:43:29.870
You can stay here if
you help in the orchard.

246
00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:32.000
I'm not a farmer.

247
00:43:32.670 --> 00:43:36.670
-And you know not how to hunt?
-Yes I know how to hunt.

248
00:43:37.650 --> 00:43:39.780
There is some game on this island.

249
00:43:40.750 --> 00:43:42.150
But no. you cannot hunt.

250
00:43:42.230 --> 00:43:44.150
You cannot even draw a bow.

251
00:43:44.230 --> 00:43:46.620
-I can draw my bow.
-It's mostly rabbits.

252
00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:49.600
-Do you know how to trap?
-I know how to trap.

253
00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:55.580
Good. but no more than six traps.
or the population will not sustain.

254
00:43:55.670 --> 00:43:58.030
Can you manage six traps?

255
00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:03.480
I can manage six traps.

256
00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:06.670
Good.

257
00:44:07.940 --> 00:44:10.880
And the rest of your time.
you may help in the orchard.

258
00:44:46.960 --> 00:44:48.920
Are you trying to flee?

259
00:44:52.570 --> 00:44:54.000
You are quiet.

260
00:44:55.590 --> 00:44:57.990
I'm quiet and slow.

261
00:44:59.170 --> 00:45:02.830
You are quiet. but you need to be slow.

262
00:45:02.920 --> 00:45:05.450
-You are crippled.
-Ah. you're a leper.

263
00:45:06.700 --> 00:45:10.470
It's alright to be slow.
We are safe here.

264
00:45:10.550 --> 00:45:13.060
That's quite a thing to say.
You know that?

265
00:45:13.140 --> 00:45:15.380
I know that.
Because she has made us safe.

266
00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:16.870
Your Prioress?

267
00:45:18.900 --> 00:45:20.300
She was like us.

268
00:45:21.210 --> 00:45:25.170
She knew great sorrow and great pain.

269
00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:27.430
Widowed young.

270
00:45:29.170 --> 00:45:30.980
But through that sorrow.

271
00:45:31.070 --> 00:45:33.100
She found the strength to heal us.

272
00:45:33.320 --> 00:45:35.590
You do not look like you've been healed.

273
00:45:39.140 --> 00:45:43.270
The Prioress once told me a
story of a great philosopher.

274
00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:47.030
The greatest philosopher of his time.

275
00:45:47.790 --> 00:45:51.230
But one day.
his king turned against him.

276
00:45:51.310 --> 00:45:54.630
Threw him in the dungeon to be
tortured and executed.

277
00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:57.200
But in his misery...

278
00:45:57.830 --> 00:45:59.820
when he had nothing.

279
00:45:59.900 --> 00:46:03.030
an angel came to the
philosopher. and she spoke to him.

280
00:46:04.170 --> 00:46:08.680
And from her. he
learned that it didn't matter

281
00:46:08.770 --> 00:46:12.080
if this whole world was misery.

282
00:46:13.100 --> 00:46:15.030
If all he had was death.

283
00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:21.630
Because he had one thing that
could never be touched or taken.

284
00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:25.200
He had his mind.

285
00:46:26.800 --> 00:46:28.430
And in his mind.

286
00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:31.300
he had God.

287
00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:36.830
It's never too late to find peace.

288
00:46:38.380 --> 00:46:40.270
What are you doing?

289
00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:42.230
I row across every day.

290
00:46:42.600 --> 00:46:46.520
Your friend was strong enough to take
you. but some are not. so I ferry them.

291
00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:48.960
-Will you take me across?
-I will not.

292
00:46:49.040 --> 00:46:51.410
You can row yourself when you're stronger.

293
00:46:52.430 --> 00:46:54.130
For now. work on your tasks.

294
00:46:54.210 --> 00:46:56.320
Trapping. I hear.
-I will hunt.

295
00:46:56.400 --> 00:46:57.800
No. you can't hunt.

296
00:47:02.920 --> 00:47:04.150
Leper.

297
00:47:04.630 --> 00:47:06.800
What happened to that great philosopher?

298
00:47:07.900 --> 00:47:10.600
He was tortured and executed. of course.

299
00:47:12.270 --> 00:47:13.670
Of course.

300
00:49:14.040 --> 00:49:15.540
Oi! Oi!

301
00:49:16.400 --> 00:49:20.650
The leper brought someone.
from the far shore.

302
00:50:00.500 --> 00:50:01.900
Papa's dead.

303
00:51:17.200 --> 00:51:18.600
How is the girl?

304
00:51:32.070 --> 00:51:34.000
Let me show you my trees.

305
00:51:44.630 --> 00:51:47.230
These are the elderberries.

306
00:51:47.470 --> 00:51:49.600
The harvest late in the summer.

307
00:51:50.270 --> 00:51:52.400
Do you know what you were before this?

308
00:51:52.630 --> 00:51:55.630
You'll have to favour
this side. for my hearing.

309
00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:01.030
Pears. I harvest just after...

310
00:52:03.900 --> 00:52:06.000
And what was I before this?

311
00:52:06.080 --> 00:52:08.830
A sell-sword. at best.

312
00:52:09.070 --> 00:52:10.600
At best. certainly.

313
00:52:10.690 --> 00:52:12.830
We have a way about us.

314
00:52:13.900 --> 00:52:15.460
Do you remember the trees?

315
00:52:15.550 --> 00:52:17.970
-Pears and Elderberries.
-Wonderful.

316
00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:22.240
Some of them know...

317
00:52:23.400 --> 00:52:26.870
But the Prioress does
not care who we were.

318
00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:31.430
And the apples harvest in the autumn.

319
00:52:32.570 --> 00:52:36.140
Did she...
speak of what happened to her?

320
00:52:37.380 --> 00:52:39.350
The Prioress is tending to the girl.

321
00:52:39.430 --> 00:52:42.170
You should speak with
her if you are concerned.

322
00:52:45.600 --> 00:52:47.000
What were the trees?

323
00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:51.370
Pears. apples and elderberries.

324
00:52:52.970 --> 00:52:54.370
Wonderful.

325
00:53:06.160 --> 00:53:07.890
This will be your last letting.

326
00:53:09.370 --> 00:53:11.680
Although your body still has much healing.

327
00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:16.470
You look tired.

328
00:53:17.300 --> 00:53:18.700
I am.

329
00:53:19.870 --> 00:53:21.630
But I have been tired before.

330
00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:25.100
The child doesn't sleep.

331
00:53:28.370 --> 00:53:29.770
What happened to her?

332
00:53:31.400 --> 00:53:32.830
Terrible things.

333
00:53:35.970 --> 00:53:38.580
-She told you her story?
-No. she doesn't speak.

334
00:53:39.120 --> 00:53:41.200
She doesn't eat. she doesn't sleep.

335
00:53:48.830 --> 00:53:50.230
What is her name?

336
00:53:57.840 --> 00:53:59.240
Margaret.

337
00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:03.400
Who is she?

338
00:54:05.600 --> 00:54:07.000
I met her father.

339
00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:09.200
A farmer.

340
00:54:09.770 --> 00:54:11.170
Well. he is dead.

341
00:54:11.670 --> 00:54:14.070
-It seems.
-And the mother?

342
00:54:14.500 --> 00:54:17.000
I think dead.

343
00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:19.210
I don't know. Dead past.

344
00:54:19.990 --> 00:54:21.390
Slain?

345
00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:23.770
Perhaps.

346
00:54:28.830 --> 00:54:30.630
You lie very well.

347
00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:41.230
Did the child see?

348
00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:44.960
She could have.

349
00:54:47.680 --> 00:54:49.690
It's much for a child to see.

350
00:54:59.600 --> 00:55:01.520
I'm sorry about your friend.

351
00:55:05.570 --> 00:55:06.970
Thank you.

352
00:55:08.170 --> 00:55:09.830
Do you like me to pray for him?

353
00:55:14.430 --> 00:55:15.830
As you wish.

354
00:55:19.450 --> 00:55:20.980
What was his name?

355
00:55:25.170 --> 00:55:26.570
Edward.

356
00:55:28.670 --> 00:55:30.070
Edward.

357
00:55:33.030 --> 00:55:37.430
<i>Be not your heart afraid. for ye
believe in God. and ye believe in me.</i>

358
00:55:39.070 --> 00:55:42.040
<i>In the house of my Father
there are many rooms.</i>

359
00:55:43.300 --> 00:55:45.700
<i>And when I make ready for you a place.</i>

360
00:55:46.430 --> 00:55:49.070
<i>I shall come. and take thee to myself.</i>

361
00:55:49.970 --> 00:55:53.370
<i>For where I am. ye may be also.</i>

362
00:55:55.370 --> 00:55:57.800
<i>And whither I go. ye shall know the way.</i>

363
00:56:19.790 --> 00:56:21.190
-Margaret!
-She stabbed me!

364
00:56:22.390 --> 00:56:23.790
Margaret.

365
00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:27.970
It's all right.

366
00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:30.470
Margaret!

367
00:56:30.600 --> 00:56:32.960
It's all right. Margaret. It's all right.

368
00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:39.800
She doesn't know this island.
There are boar about.

369
00:56:42.470 --> 00:56:43.870
Margaret! Margaret!

370
00:56:45.200 --> 00:56:46.600
Margaret! Margaret!

371
00:56:48.130 --> 00:56:50.830
Margaret! Margaret!

372
00:58:36.070 --> 00:58:37.470
Oi!

373
00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:40.960
Oi!

374
00:58:49.080 --> 00:58:50.480
Give it.

375
00:59:04.120 --> 00:59:05.100
Give it!

376
00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:24.270
Those men that hurt you...

377
00:59:27.430 --> 00:59:29.190
do they know you're here?

378
00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:43.400
What is my name?

379
00:59:49.470 --> 00:59:50.870
Say my name.

380
00:59:52.770 --> 00:59:54.170
Randolph.

381
00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:00.750
That's right.

382
01:00:06.300 --> 01:00:07.700
Who is Little John?

383
01:00:10.170 --> 01:00:12.900
That name is nonsense
and you should never speak it.

384
01:00:13.600 --> 01:00:17.230
And if you speak it. a cat will come
in the night and take your tongue.

385
01:00:27.540 --> 01:00:28.560
It's all right.

386
01:00:31.600 --> 01:00:33.000
Go to sleep.

387
01:00:40.270 --> 01:00:41.760
I'll watch the storm.

388
01:00:46.050 --> 01:00:47.980
It's all right. they know.

389
01:00:51.870 --> 01:00:53.270
Close your eyes.

390
01:00:58.210 --> 01:00:59.610
You can sleep.

391
01:01:04.480 --> 01:01:05.880
Sleep.

392
01:01:44.300 --> 01:01:46.430
Thank you for bringing her back.

393
01:01:48.800 --> 01:01:50.200
It was nothing.

394
01:01:55.500 --> 01:01:57.900
Do you know the story of this Priory?

395
01:01:58.380 --> 01:01:59.780
No.

396
01:02:02.100 --> 01:02:07.370
In ages before history. this was
a holy site to the ancient Druids.

397
01:02:09.300 --> 01:02:11.300
They worshipped unknown gods.

398
01:02:12.900 --> 01:02:14.960
Worshipped in these woods.

399
01:02:15.920 --> 01:02:17.790
Then the Romans came long ago.

400
01:02:17.870 --> 01:02:21.710
they sensed the magic of this
place. so they built their temples.

401
01:02:23.400 --> 01:02:27.050
And people upon people sensed it.
and they came here to worship.

402
01:02:28.370 --> 01:02:30.320
Countless gods. tribe after tribe.

403
01:02:30.400 --> 01:02:33.430
that would not even know
how to speak to each other.

404
01:02:34.500 --> 01:02:36.970
And yet. we are all pulled to this place.

405
01:02:38.890 --> 01:02:41.460
Do you believe that there
is Magic on this island?

406
01:02:43.670 --> 01:02:45.900
I believe there is power in it.

407
01:02:48.430 --> 01:02:50.800
I have seen the power in stories.

408
01:02:53.270 --> 01:02:56.870
They can be used to make
men do terrible things.

409
01:02:57.720 --> 01:02:59.240
And then those...

410
01:02:59.690 --> 01:03:01.920
terrible things become stories...

411
01:03:02.630 --> 01:03:04.030
and stories.

412
01:03:08.220 --> 01:03:09.280
No.

413
01:03:10.090 --> 01:03:11.950
You cannot trust any of them.

414
01:03:12.430 --> 01:03:14.630
We cannot be trusted with them.

415
01:03:16.800 --> 01:03:19.800
Knives cut bread as well as they do flesh.

416
01:03:21.360 --> 01:03:23.030
It's a question of balance.

417
01:03:23.800 --> 01:03:25.470
Does balance have a say?

418
01:03:28.030 --> 01:03:30.900
I think if balance didn't have some say.

419
01:03:31.430 --> 01:03:33.170
we wouldn't be here.

420
01:03:35.230 --> 01:03:39.170
This world would not be here and...

421
01:03:40.600 --> 01:03:42.770
and we would not be sharing these words.

422
01:03:43.500 --> 01:03:45.430
Do you ever consider that?

423
01:03:47.270 --> 01:03:51.720
The incredible precision of balance.
over such an expanse of time.

424
01:03:53.030 --> 01:03:56.890
The balance it takes to
create a word. any specific word

425
01:03:57.140 --> 01:04:00.200
that can pass between lips and...

426
01:04:02.030 --> 01:04:04.030
be understood by two minds.

427
01:04:11.770 --> 01:04:13.170
Randolph.

428
01:04:16.870 --> 01:04:18.270
Thank you.

429
01:05:37.070 --> 01:05:38.470
Not hungry?

430
01:05:40.070 --> 01:05:41.190
No?

431
01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:16.030
I will be dying soon.

432
01:06:17.170 --> 01:06:18.570
How do you know?

433
01:06:20.700 --> 01:06:23.170
I could feel it inside.

434
01:06:25.270 --> 01:06:27.000
What does it feel like?

435
01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:30.600
It feels right.

436
01:06:42.600 --> 01:06:44.030
There's someone there.

437
01:06:46.900 --> 01:06:48.770
The waters have been busy.

438
01:06:52.100 --> 01:06:54.870
Start around the feet. Little cuts.

439
01:06:55.430 --> 01:06:56.830
Good. other one.

440
01:06:59.700 --> 01:07:01.100
No.

441
01:07:04.770 --> 01:07:05.840
Good.

442
01:07:06.150 --> 01:07:08.070
Right. now let's tear down the front.

443
01:07:08.150 --> 01:07:10.150
Gut down the belly. Good.

444
01:07:13.810 --> 01:07:14.900
Watch this.

445
01:07:15.710 --> 01:07:17.020
Just like that.

446
01:07:17.110 --> 01:07:19.270
That's it. You do the other one.

447
01:07:20.700 --> 01:07:23.680
That's it. That's it. Hold.

448
01:07:59.660 --> 01:08:01.770
You are a brave young man.

449
01:08:03.070 --> 01:08:04.470
Thank you. Sister.

450
01:08:06.100 --> 01:08:07.500
Are you hungry. Arthur?

451
01:08:11.070 --> 01:08:12.670
I am. Sister.

452
01:08:12.980 --> 01:08:17.830
Sarah will fix you up a good
supper tonight. Herring stew.

453
01:08:19.890 --> 01:08:21.290
Do you like that?

454
01:08:22.820 --> 01:08:24.660
Where do you come from. Arthur?

455
01:08:28.100 --> 01:08:29.840
My family farm toward Keswick.

456
01:08:29.920 --> 01:08:31.830
-Towards Keswick.
-Yes sir.

457
01:08:31.910 --> 01:08:33.910
-Randolph.
-Randolph.

458
01:08:34.070 --> 01:08:37.720
-Towards Keswick.
-The leper says you seek your niece.

459
01:08:37.800 --> 01:08:39.490
-I do.
-Were you set upon?

460
01:08:41.600 --> 01:08:43.430
-I was.
-On the road?

461
01:08:44.850 --> 01:08:45.750
Yes.

462
01:08:45.840 --> 01:08:49.100
-We are safe here.
-On which road?

463
01:08:49.870 --> 01:08:51.870
The road to Keswick. sire.

464
01:08:53.070 --> 01:08:54.670
Thank the Lord. you survived.

465
01:08:54.750 --> 01:08:56.050
I do thank the Lord.

466
01:08:56.130 --> 01:08:59.470
How about honeyed pears
after supper for being so brave?

467
01:09:02.500 --> 01:09:03.900
Thank you. Sister.

468
01:09:18.230 --> 01:09:19.630
Little Margaret...

469
01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:22.400
A man Arthur...

470
01:09:22.600 --> 01:09:25.200
Did you ever see him before
you came to the Priory?

471
01:09:28.900 --> 01:09:30.300
Margaret.

472
01:09:37.030 --> 01:09:38.430
The men...

473
01:09:39.170 --> 01:09:40.830
The men who hurt your papa...

474
01:09:43.230 --> 01:09:44.870
did you see their faces?

475
01:09:46.200 --> 01:09:47.700
Papa said to run.

476
01:09:58.670 --> 01:10:00.230
Papa stopped praying.

477
01:10:01.800 --> 01:10:03.200
He was angry.

478
01:10:04.570 --> 01:10:06.030
He prayed in his mind.

479
01:10:09.100 --> 01:10:10.700
What was papa's name?

480
01:10:14.800 --> 01:10:16.200
Your papa is your papa.

481
01:10:28.800 --> 01:10:30.200
Bring it here.

482
01:10:39.630 --> 01:10:41.800
Oh. this is fine work.

483
01:10:47.400 --> 01:10:49.770
Do you see it favours a bend here.

484
01:10:51.750 --> 01:10:55.250
Now you have to balance it.
so it bends evenly.

485
01:10:55.800 --> 01:10:58.250
So. this part here needs to be thin.

486
01:10:58.590 --> 01:10:59.990
Right?

487
01:11:04.870 --> 01:11:06.630
Can you make for me?

488
01:11:09.100 --> 01:11:10.600
I'm gonna make you a bow.

489
01:11:15.140 --> 01:11:16.540
All-right.

490
01:11:24.500 --> 01:11:28.070
Today I remembered the
story by a poet named Lucretius.

491
01:11:30.230 --> 01:11:32.430
He wrote of what are called atoms.

492
01:11:33.860 --> 01:11:37.990
If you pick apart the trees
and people and stones.

493
01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:42.670
these would be the
smallest. indivisible pieces

494
01:11:42.750 --> 01:11:45.250
that make up everything in creation.

495
01:11:46.700 --> 01:11:51.630
And these atoms are
sailing through the void.

496
01:11:54.150 --> 01:11:57.690
And sometimes. for no reason
at all they change their course.

497
01:12:00.300 --> 01:12:02.700
Least amount. not even a hair.

498
01:12:07.170 --> 01:12:11.260
And if it weren't for that small

499
01:12:11.900 --> 01:12:15.350
unpredictable change forcing the atoms to

500
01:12:15.430 --> 01:12:17.590
cross and weave with each other.

501
01:12:21.170 --> 01:12:23.770
nothing at all under
the heavens would exist.

502
01:15:08.150 --> 01:15:10.050
Nice You're good.

503
01:15:10.140 --> 01:15:11.340
Harder.

504
01:15:11.420 --> 01:15:13.490
That's it. Good.

505
01:15:22.240 --> 01:15:23.640
Cut that one.

506
01:15:24.830 --> 01:15:27.170
Good. there we go.

507
01:15:27.970 --> 01:15:29.370
Good.

508
01:15:31.800 --> 01:15:33.730
Which one do you think for your bow?

509
01:15:34.300 --> 01:15:35.700
Let's have a little look.

510
01:15:36.570 --> 01:15:37.970
Okay.

511
01:15:38.470 --> 01:15:40.430
There you go. They are both good.

512
01:15:51.770 --> 01:15:53.070
Margaret.

513
01:15:53.150 --> 01:15:55.280
Margaret. come play.

514
01:16:35.440 --> 01:16:36.840
Arthur.

515
01:16:37.670 --> 01:16:40.570
-Do you know how to trap?
-Yes.

516
01:16:40.700 --> 01:16:42.970
Good. I need a strong hand.

517
01:16:56.400 --> 01:16:57.970
Does your family have land?

518
01:16:59.470 --> 01:17:00.870
Yes.

519
01:17:02.570 --> 01:17:04.200
How many of you are there?

520
01:17:06.000 --> 01:17:07.570
I don't know.

521
01:17:14.300 --> 01:17:15.700
Are you alright?

522
01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:21.170
I'm... I'm not as young as I once was.

523
01:17:23.630 --> 01:17:25.170
Could use a hand up is all.

524
01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:31.400
Thank you.

525
01:17:32.830 --> 01:17:34.930
They delivered you quite a blow.

526
01:17:36.800 --> 01:17:38.300
-Yes.
-Who did it?

527
01:17:40.600 --> 01:17:42.000
A man.

528
01:17:42.400 --> 01:17:45.170
Some men. Bandits.

529
01:17:45.250 --> 01:17:47.550
A man? Bandits?

530
01:17:47.630 --> 01:17:49.700
-Yes.
-May I look?

531
01:17:55.400 --> 01:17:56.800
Quite a blow.

532
01:17:58.500 --> 01:18:00.070
You're lucky you survived.

533
01:18:00.150 --> 01:18:01.790
-You are a lucky boy.
-Yes.

534
01:18:01.870 --> 01:18:03.800
You should be thankful to be alive.

535
01:18:04.270 --> 01:18:05.300
Yes...

536
01:18:05.380 --> 01:18:07.110
It was a quarterstaff.

537
01:18:14.100 --> 01:18:16.360
Lucky it didn't take your head off.

538
01:18:21.030 --> 01:18:22.430
<i>Randolph!</i>

539
01:18:25.200 --> 01:18:26.600
<i>Randolph!</i>

540
01:18:29.310 --> 01:18:30.710
Moshe!

541
01:18:34.230 --> 01:18:36.970
The Prioress said to come.

542
01:19:18.450 --> 01:19:20.010
Are you in great pain?

543
01:19:29.600 --> 01:19:32.270
Do you remember the trees?

544
01:19:34.230 --> 01:19:36.510
Pears. apples and Elderberries.

545
01:19:38.800 --> 01:19:40.050
Wonderful.

546
01:19:50.600 --> 01:19:55.710
You know that you are the most important
person in little Margaret's life.

547
01:19:57.770 --> 01:19:59.060
I'm not important.

548
01:20:11.560 --> 01:20:15.200
Think of all the people whose lives
you've crossed.

549
01:20:18.310 --> 01:20:21.430
We were important somehow. to all of them.

550
01:20:28.580 --> 01:20:32.050
Do you know the story
of Guy of Gisborne...

551
01:20:33.690 --> 01:20:35.120
and Robin Hood?

552
01:20:40.420 --> 01:20:41.590
Yes.

553
01:20:46.510 --> 01:20:48.950
They say you killed him.

554
01:20:51.020 --> 01:20:52.610
Did you really behead him?

555
01:20:52.700 --> 01:20:53.900
You're confused. Leper.

556
01:20:53.980 --> 01:20:55.790
I will not tell a soul.

557
01:20:58.510 --> 01:21:01.790
But don't lie to a man on his deathbed.

558
01:21:04.060 --> 01:21:05.510
So...

559
01:21:05.590 --> 01:21:07.620
did you really behead him?

560
01:21:11.120 --> 01:21:13.000
There was no Guy of Gisborne.

561
01:21:14.050 --> 01:21:16.500
Just one of many tales
that were passed along.

562
01:21:18.910 --> 01:21:20.580
But I've beheaded other men.

563
01:21:28.210 --> 01:21:30.410
You really don't remember?

564
01:21:32.590 --> 01:21:33.650
No.

565
01:21:34.760 --> 01:21:36.920
Think about that name.

566
01:21:41.080 --> 01:21:43.900
There was a Guy of Gisborne.

567
01:21:47.360 --> 01:21:49.450
But you did not behead him.

568
01:21:51.910 --> 01:21:53.720
You cut off his ear.

569
01:22:01.400 --> 01:22:02.900
You said...

570
01:22:02.980 --> 01:22:06.500
in another life.
you would share a drink with him.

571
01:22:08.580 --> 01:22:10.150
Do you remember that.

572
01:22:22.040 --> 01:22:24.840
We seem to have found another life.

573
01:22:32.220 --> 01:22:33.300
Now...

574
01:22:33.390 --> 01:22:37.610
There is one cruelty I would
ask you to not bring about...

575
01:22:40.240 --> 01:22:44.210
You will guard the
orchard until you. too. die.

576
01:22:47.470 --> 01:22:50.570
You will serve the Prioress...

577
01:22:51.370 --> 01:22:55.070
and the people of this
Priory. past and future.

578
01:22:59.670 --> 01:23:03.700
But at no point in that time.

579
01:23:06.020 --> 01:23:10.620
in those good and peaceful years...

580
01:23:13.470 --> 01:23:17.270
will you tell the Prioress
who you really are.

581
01:23:23.070 --> 01:23:24.470
Why?

582
01:23:26.870 --> 01:23:28.270
Because...

583
01:23:29.870 --> 01:23:31.920
One of those...

584
01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:35.200
nameless. faceless death in
the shadows of your mind...

585
01:23:38.070 --> 01:23:40.000
was. in another life...

586
01:23:42.640 --> 01:23:44.040
her beloved.

587
01:23:52.490 --> 01:23:53.900
Promise me.

588
01:23:58.870 --> 01:24:00.270
Robin.

589
01:24:01.770 --> 01:24:03.300
Promise me.

590
01:25:34.870 --> 01:25:36.270
Goodbye. Brigid.

591
01:25:49.660 --> 01:25:51.060
Arthur.

592
01:25:53.220 --> 01:25:54.620
Come.

593
01:25:57.550 --> 01:25:59.700
There is a child on the far shore.

594
01:26:00.980 --> 01:26:02.380
Perhaps it's your niece.

595
01:26:04.600 --> 01:26:07.150
The Leper said you sought your lost niece.

596
01:26:08.170 --> 01:26:09.100
Yes.

597
01:26:10.170 --> 01:26:12.990
-Could it be her?
-We shall see.

598
01:26:51.870 --> 01:26:54.030
I do not see signs of anyone.

599
01:26:55.170 --> 01:26:56.630
We should wait.

600
01:26:57.400 --> 01:26:58.970
Maybe they'll return.

601
01:27:21.030 --> 01:27:22.430
What is your name?

602
01:27:26.280 --> 01:27:27.680
Arthur.

603
01:27:28.780 --> 01:27:30.920
Don't waste time lying to me.

604
01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:32.430
What is your real name?

605
01:27:36.940 --> 01:27:38.340
Godwyn.

606
01:27:41.400 --> 01:27:43.860
You are deciding. Godwyn.

607
01:27:43.940 --> 01:27:46.850
whether to do the deed yourself.

608
01:27:47.250 --> 01:27:49.450
or to fetch your family?

609
01:27:52.170 --> 01:27:53.220
What deed?

610
01:27:53.300 --> 01:27:55.740
How many men have you killed. Godwyn?

611
01:27:56.900 --> 01:28:00.000
How many children have you killed?

612
01:28:05.170 --> 01:28:08.170
I have killed so many. I
could not give you a count.

613
01:28:09.880 --> 01:28:11.770
For longer than you've been alive.

614
01:28:11.850 --> 01:28:13.650
I've been killing kin of those.

615
01:28:13.740 --> 01:28:16.730
I killed a lifetime ago. who I
don't remember in the first.

616
01:28:16.820 --> 01:28:19.120
Who meant nothing to me at that time.

617
01:28:20.490 --> 01:28:25.070
But their brothers and their children.
the grandchildren. they remember me.

618
01:28:26.070 --> 01:28:28.140
And so now I must kill them.

619
01:28:28.990 --> 01:28:30.420
Again and again...

620
01:28:31.630 --> 01:28:35.400
in different forms. like shades... again.

621
01:28:36.770 --> 01:28:38.900
And again. it never ceases.

622
01:28:42.500 --> 01:28:44.300
It's a curse. Godwyn.

623
01:28:46.210 --> 01:28:50.410
It's one that you bring on
yourself. even if done through duty.

624
01:28:51.430 --> 01:28:53.970
It cares not about your duty.

625
01:28:54.430 --> 01:28:57.670
This world cares only about blood...

626
01:28:59.070 --> 01:29:01.300
and blood is all it will give in return.

627
01:29:04.180 --> 01:29:06.650
Do you want to kill a child. Godwin?

628
01:29:09.430 --> 01:29:13.450
Do you want to be responsible
for the killing of a little girl?

629
01:29:16.610 --> 01:29:17.810
No.

630
01:29:29.780 --> 01:29:31.220
Your father is dead?

631
01:29:32.630 --> 01:29:34.030
And your uncles?

632
01:29:36.970 --> 01:29:38.900
I'm the all that's left.

633
01:29:43.230 --> 01:29:45.030
Who else yet lives. Godwyn?

634
01:29:47.200 --> 01:29:48.600
My mother.

635
01:29:50.070 --> 01:29:51.470
My aunts.

636
01:29:52.700 --> 01:29:54.100
My sisters.

637
01:29:54.470 --> 01:29:56.230
You have a home. Godwyn.

638
01:29:58.470 --> 01:30:00.800
-Yes.
-Go home.

639
01:30:01.900 --> 01:30:04.670
Tell your family that all
blood debts have been paid.

640
01:30:05.230 --> 01:30:06.970
They will all be paid someday.

641
01:30:09.220 --> 01:30:10.620
Sleep in your own bed.

642
01:30:11.570 --> 01:30:15.830
Hold dear the life you will
yet share with your kin.

643
01:30:17.490 --> 01:30:19.460
And if you return here...

644
01:30:20.470 --> 01:30:24.370
you will have wasted this
chance at life that I give you now

645
01:30:25.470 --> 01:30:29.270
and I will cut your throat
and never think of you again.

646
01:30:36.000 --> 01:30:37.400
Go now.

647
01:30:39.660 --> 01:30:41.060
Don't look back.

648
01:31:35.620 --> 01:31:37.450
I thought you were departed.

649
01:31:47.340 --> 01:31:49.210
I'm Robin. the outlaw.

650
01:31:52.700 --> 01:31:56.470
You need to know that I am a monster.

651
01:31:58.700 --> 01:32:00.300
I'm not one Randolph.

652
01:32:02.960 --> 01:32:04.630
I am the outlaw...

653
01:32:05.000 --> 01:32:06.400
Robin Hood.

654
01:32:21.700 --> 01:32:23.100
I'm sorry.

655
01:34:23.200 --> 01:34:24.970
Tell me how I should leave.

656
01:34:27.230 --> 01:34:28.800
I will go now.

657
01:34:36.630 --> 01:34:38.030
Get in the bed.

658
01:34:57.870 --> 01:34:59.570
-Brigid.
-Lie down.

659
01:38:25.100 --> 01:38:27.300
You burned my husband alive.

660
01:38:32.700 --> 01:38:36.480
I dream that he was already dead.
but why else did you bar the door?

661
01:38:41.570 --> 01:38:45.700
It felt like a lifetime. searching
the ashes of our home.

662
01:38:48.820 --> 01:38:50.920
And he looked so small.

663
01:38:52.760 --> 01:38:56.470
Curled up in the corner.
with so much of him gone.

664
01:39:01.030 --> 01:39:04.180
And as much as I dream.
I know he was alive.

665
01:39:08.920 --> 01:39:13.600
Because. until the very end. he had
wrapped himself around our children.

666
01:40:01.800 --> 01:40:03.200
Randolph.

667
01:40:05.400 --> 01:40:06.870
It is me.

668
01:41:00.830 --> 01:41:03.270
People speak of Robin Hood...

669
01:41:08.100 --> 01:41:09.500
Tell stories...

670
01:41:16.070 --> 01:41:17.470
They're all lies.

671
01:41:21.430 --> 01:41:24.190
Lies that I told long ago...

672
01:41:25.800 --> 01:41:27.800
So that fools would...

673
01:41:29.170 --> 01:41:31.100
Follow me into the dark.

674
01:41:40.630 --> 01:41:42.030
Robin.

675
01:41:48.000 --> 01:41:50.170
What are they doing to you?

676
01:41:55.870 --> 01:41:57.570
Don't be afraid.

677
01:41:59.800 --> 01:42:02.500
I'll rescue you from this place.

678
01:42:04.790 --> 01:42:06.860
I will rescue Little Margaret.

679
01:42:08.590 --> 01:42:11.600
We're gonna start a new life together.

680
01:42:12.300 --> 01:42:13.700
Edward.

681
01:42:17.700 --> 01:42:19.670
Tell me about your wife.

682
01:42:29.430 --> 01:42:30.830
My wife...

683
01:42:33.580 --> 01:42:34.980
Margaret.

684
01:42:38.890 --> 01:42:40.290
Margaret.

685
01:42:42.400 --> 01:42:44.630
My wife Margaret.

686
01:42:46.900 --> 01:42:48.430
Paint a portrait.

687
01:42:51.170 --> 01:42:52.570
Paint a portrait?

688
01:42:56.770 --> 01:42:58.200
She has hair...

689
01:43:00.290 --> 01:43:01.690
red like...

690
01:43:03.100 --> 01:43:05.100
the setting sun.

691
01:43:08.100 --> 01:43:11.170
Like the setting summer sun.

692
01:43:18.470 --> 01:43:19.850
Red like...

693
01:43:19.930 --> 01:43:22.700
a setting summer...

694
01:43:23.540 --> 01:43:24.940
Sun...

695
01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:43.930
Robin...

696
01:43:50.300 --> 01:43:52.670
Have you found your right death?

697
01:44:53.170 --> 01:44:55.270
I'm ready to finish it.

698
01:45:02.400 --> 01:45:04.500
I owe this life to you.

699
01:45:11.970 --> 01:45:13.470
It is monstrous...

700
01:45:18.030 --> 01:45:20.370
but I owe this life to you.

701
01:45:20.950 --> 01:45:22.350
You owe me nothing.

702
01:45:27.570 --> 01:45:30.100
I have never taken a life before.

703
01:45:34.200 --> 01:45:36.830
It can be as if pruning the flower.

704
01:45:39.120 --> 01:45:40.790
Well. It should not be.

705
01:45:41.500 --> 01:45:43.000
It should not.

706
01:45:44.270 --> 01:45:45.930
But it can.

707
01:45:51.430 --> 01:45:54.030
I help those who come to this island.

708
01:45:56.930 --> 01:45:58.400
I heal them.

709
01:46:02.110 --> 01:46:03.230
Please.

710
01:46:08.700 --> 01:46:10.200
Heal me.

711
01:47:05.830 --> 01:47:07.270
Little Margaret...

712
01:47:13.070 --> 01:47:15.470
Your father's name was John.

713
01:47:24.670 --> 01:47:30.060
I knew him for many years.
before he was your papa.

714
01:47:36.170 --> 01:47:37.570
I met him...

715
01:47:39.070 --> 01:47:41.200
crossing a bridge one day...

716
01:47:42.600 --> 01:47:44.630
over a rushing river.

717
01:47:47.430 --> 01:47:49.030
He was stubborn.

718
01:47:51.970 --> 01:47:54.230
He would not yield.

719
01:47:56.170 --> 01:47:57.800
Not to any men.

720
01:47:58.830 --> 01:48:00.800
Not even to me.

721
01:48:03.700 --> 01:48:07.700
So we wrestled on that bridge.

722
01:48:09.710 --> 01:48:12.580
Striking back and forth.

723
01:48:14.770 --> 01:48:17.600
I whacked him on the side of the head.

724
01:48:19.900 --> 01:48:22.320
He struck me in the stomach.

725
01:48:23.430 --> 01:48:26.030
I wobbled on that bridge...

726
01:48:27.610 --> 01:48:29.010
splashed.

727
01:48:30.090 --> 01:48:31.990
He knocked me on my bum.

728
01:48:36.270 --> 01:48:38.500
Once I dragged myself out...

729
01:48:39.430 --> 01:48:40.830
drenched to the bone...

730
01:48:42.750 --> 01:48:44.210
we embraced.

731
01:48:47.570 --> 01:48:51.370
We called your papa Little John.

732
01:48:53.030 --> 01:48:55.200
And we lived for many years...

733
01:48:58.400 --> 01:49:01.670
as outlaws in the Greenwood.

734
01:49:05.170 --> 01:49:06.570
We had feasts.

735
01:49:09.610 --> 01:49:13.440
We gave silver to the meek.

736
01:49:30.570 --> 01:49:32.570
But we stole that silver.

737
01:49:38.600 --> 01:49:40.000
We stole it...

738
01:49:43.270 --> 01:49:44.770
From bad people.

739
01:49:49.400 --> 01:49:50.800
Do you understand?

740
01:49:53.370 --> 01:49:54.770
Bad people.

741
01:50:09.800 --> 01:50:11.200
Your father...

742
01:50:12.460 --> 01:50:14.380
He would want me to tell you...

743
01:50:20.260 --> 01:50:22.560
Because he loved you so. dear.

744
01:50:26.850 --> 01:50:29.250
You must never tell a soul.

745
01:50:30.960 --> 01:50:33.460
Not even the children you play with.

746
01:50:34.770 --> 01:50:38.770
You must never tell them your papa's name.

747
01:50:42.770 --> 01:50:45.030
There are bad people out there.

748
01:50:47.630 --> 01:50:51.270
And they are angry with your papa.

749
01:50:55.610 --> 01:50:57.980
And so they are angry with you.

750
01:51:02.800 --> 01:51:04.830
Can we keep that secret?

751
01:51:07.430 --> 01:51:10.030
I can keep that secret. Little Margaret.

752
01:51:12.580 --> 01:51:13.980
Can you?

753
01:51:18.090 --> 01:51:19.490
Good.

754
01:51:22.030 --> 01:51:23.630
Now. come beside me.

755
01:51:33.630 --> 01:51:35.030
Take this.

756
01:51:36.720 --> 01:51:38.280
Why was he little?

757
01:51:39.050 --> 01:51:40.450
What?

758
01:51:41.450 --> 01:51:43.610
Why was my papa called "Little"?

759
01:51:49.440 --> 01:51:51.970
Because he was little when I found him.

760
01:51:53.570 --> 01:51:54.970
Like you.

761
01:52:02.950 --> 01:52:04.350
String it.

762
01:52:27.320 --> 01:52:30.520
Bend it with your leg.
as you saw me do.

763
01:52:51.750 --> 01:52:53.150
Go to the window.

764
01:53:17.430 --> 01:53:18.830
Knock an arrow.

765
01:53:27.430 --> 01:53:32.300
Find a point.
where the waters meet the sky.

766
01:53:37.370 --> 01:53:39.700
Pull the arrow to your mouth.

767
01:53:43.400 --> 01:53:44.800
And hold.

768
01:53:46.570 --> 01:53:48.830
I'll tell you when to loose.

769
01:53:51.830 --> 01:53:53.370
And when I do...

770
01:53:54.260 --> 01:53:56.090
you are not letting go...

771
01:53:58.770 --> 01:54:01.370
you simply are not holding on any more.

772
01:54:08.590 --> 01:54:10.120
Watch that target.

773
01:54:13.470 --> 01:54:15.900
Your body will always be moving.

774
01:54:19.170 --> 01:54:23.630
Feel when the arrow will fly true.

775
01:54:26.880 --> 01:54:28.750
You're going to find a dance.

776
01:54:31.270 --> 01:54:33.700
Hold until I tell you to loose...

777
01:54:37.260 --> 01:54:38.860
You are strong.

778
01:54:40.000 --> 01:54:41.400
Feel...

779
01:54:43.200 --> 01:54:44.600
The sway...

780
01:54:48.030 --> 01:54:49.430
That dance...

781
01:54:56.430 --> 01:54:57.830
Now loose.

782
01:55:10.440 --> 01:55:14.810
<i>Transcribed by Clarity</i>
